
# app.py
from flask import Flask
app = Flask(__name__)
@app.route('/')
def home():
    return "Hello from Flask in Docker!"
if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run(host='0.0.0.0', port=5000)

# requirements.txt 
flask

# Dockerfile

FROM python:3.9-slim
# Set working directory
WORKDIR /app
# Copy requirements and install dependencies
COPY requirements.txt .
RUN pip install -r requirements.txt
# Copy app code
COPY app.py .
# Expose Flask port
EXPOSE 5000
# Run the app
CMD ["python", "app.py"]

-------------------------------------------------------

 *Step 5: Build Docker Image*
Run the following command in the project directory:
docker image build -t flask-docker-app .

Step 6: Run Docker Container
Run the container and map port 5000:
docker container run -d -p 5000:5000 --name flask_container flask-docker-app

Step 7: Test the App
Open browser or use curl:
http://localhost:5000
displays:
Hello from Flask in Docker!
--------------------------------------------------------
##################Explanation of app.py
from flask import Flask
•	Imports the Flask class from the flask package.
•	Flask is a micro web framework in Python that helps you quickly build web applications.
app = Flask(__name__)
•	Creates a Flask application object.
•	__name__ tells Flask where to look for templates, static files, etc. (it’s the name of the current module).
 @app.route('/')
•	A route decorator.
•	Defines the URL endpoint / (root of the website).
•	When a user visits http://localhost:5000/, this function (home()) will be executed.
def home(): return "Hello from Flask in Docker!"
•	The function returns a plain text response.
•	This is what the browser shows when you hit the / route.
 if __name__ == '__main__':
•	Ensures that the app runs only if you execute the file directly (not if it’s imported as a module).
 app.run(host='0.0.0.0', port=5000)
•	Starts the Flask development server.
•	host='0.0.0.0' → Makes the app available on all network interfaces (important for Docker, otherwise it only runs inside the container).
•	port=5000 → The app will run on port 5000
